## What to do

- Check current VPN for DNS leaks, IP leaks, and WebRTC leaks via ipleak.net and dnsleaktest.com. If anything leaks, switch clients or configure routes manually through sing-box or Nekoray.
- Separate wallets by purpose: KYC exchange wallet for fiat on-ramp/off-ramp, operational no-KYC wallet on a separate IP for trading, cold hardware wallet with multisig for long-term storage.
- Write seed to steel storage and place it in a physically separate location, not a home safe.
- Switch to CoinJoin or Lightning for regular payments instead of on-chain USDT.
- Enable Tor-only mode in Sparrow or Electrum and disable clearnet fallback.
- Never sign a transaction not initiated by the operator: clipboard hijackers and fake-tx attacks via swapped QR codes cost users over 100 million USD collectively in 2024.
- For regular operations, rotate VPN servers weekly. For one-off actions — large deposits or withdrawals — use a new VPN server each time, preferably in a different jurisdiction. Ideally, burn the IP immediately after the operation and never reuse it.

## What it actually means

VPN and crypto in 2026 form a single privacy stack where each layer either reinforces the other or creates a hole. Marketing VPN providers don't work for this task: they solve "watch YouTube," not "keep bitcoin safe from a targeted attack." Self-hosted infrastructure (VLESS+Reality, own full node, hardware wallet, CoinJoin) is the minimum baseline, not the maximum. Anything below will eventually be compromised.

The next 12-24 months will bring three shifts. First: AMLD6 will zero out the reporting threshold, and any centralized exchange with a MiCA license becomes a leak point by definition. Second: chain analytics will automate via AI agents, and manual evasion methods will stop working. Third: VLESS+Reality will become the de facto standard for all jurisdictions with active filtering, while WireGuard and OpenVPN retreat to the corporate VPN niche. A stack that ignores these three trends will be obsolete by late 2027.

### Which VPN protocol to choose under heavy censorship?

VLESS+Reality on a VPS in an unblocked jurisdiction (Finland, Germany, Japan, Singapore). Fallback: Shadowsocks-2022 and AmneziaWG. WireGuard and OpenVPN don't work under these conditions as of 2026.

### Is it safe to use a browser VPN extension instead of a standalone client?

No. Extensions have access to all browser traffic, and many — especially free ones — log and sell data. A standalone system client (sing-box, Nekoray, AmneziaVPN) is the only safe option.

### Should you trust VPN providers that accept crypto payments?

Accepting crypto and keeping no logs is a marketing claim impossible to verify without audit and legal analysis. Mullvad (accepts cash by mail) and IVPN are the best in this category, but even they don't deserve 100% trust. Self-hosted is the only zero-trust option.

### Can a VPN reveal who sent a blockchain transaction?

No. A VPN hides the IP, not the sender address. If the transaction originates from a KYC exchange, its link to identity is already recorded in the exchange's database and accessible upon request from competent authorities.

### How often should VPN servers be rotated?

For regular operations, rotate exit nodes weekly. For one-off actions — large deposits or withdrawals — use a new VPN server each time, preferably in a different jurisdiction. Ideally, burn the IP immediately after the operation and never reuse it.

